  <content>
    <para id="para-00001">The direct nucleophilic acyl substitution of a carboxylic acid is difficult because  – OH is a poor leaving group <emphasis effect="bold">(<link>Section 11.3</link>)</emphasis>. Thus, it’s usually necessary to enhance the reactivity of the acid, either by using a strong acid catalyst to protonate the carboxyl and make it a better acceptor or by converting the  – OH into a better leaving group. Under the right circumstances, however, acid chlorides, anhydrides, esters, and amides can all be prepared from carboxylic acids by nucleophilic acyl substitution reactions.</para>
    <section id="sect-00001">
    <title>Conversion of Carboxylic Acids into Acid Chlorides</title>
    <para id="para-00002">In the laboratory, carboxylic acids are converted into acid chlorides by treatment with thionyl chloride, SOCl<sub>2</sub>.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00001">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which 2 4 6-Trimethylbenzoic acid in the presence of SOCl2 (highlighted in blue) and CHC3 yields 2 4 6-Trimethylbenzoyl chloride (90%) HCl and SO2 (highlighted in blue). 2 4 6-Trimethylbenzoic acid shows a benzene with C2 C4 and C6 bonded to a methyl group each and C1 bonded to a carbon double bonded to a pink oxygen and single bonded to a green hydroxyl group. 2 4 6-Trimethylbenzoyl chloride shows a benzene with C2 C4 and C6 bonded to a methyl group each and C1 bonded to a carbon double bonded to a pink oxygen and single bonded to a blue chlorine. In HCl H is highlighted in green and Cl is blue.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_03_001.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00003">This reaction occurs by a nucleophilic acyl substitution pathway in which the carboxylic acid is first converted into an acyl chlorosulfite intermediate, thereby replacing the  – OH of the acid with a much better leaving group. The chlorosulfite then reacts with a nucleophilic chloride ion. You might recall from <emphasis effect="bold"><link>Section 17.6</link></emphasis> that an analogous chlorosulfite is involved in the reaction of an alcohol with SOCl<sub>2</sub> to yield an alkyl chloride.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered" id="fig-00002">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which Carboxylic acid in the presence of SOCl2 (highlighted in blue) yields a chlorosulfite that yields an intermediate that further reacts to yield acid chloride and SO2 (highlighted in blue). The chlorosulfite and the intermediate are shown inside parentheses. Carboxylic acid shows RCOOH (green hydroxyl group). The chlorosulfite shows R bonded to carbonyl group bonded to a green oxygen bonded to sulfur that is single bonded to chlorine and double bonded to an oxygen. An arrow from a chloride ion points to the carbon. An arrow from the double bond points to the oxygen that shows four electrons. The intermediate shows R bonded to carbon bonded to a green oxygen blue chlorine and oxygen that shows six electrons. The oxygen is bonded to sulfur that is single bonded to chlorine and double bonded to an oxygen. An arrow from the electrons of oxygen points to C-O bond. An arrow from the C-green O bond points to O-S bond. An arrow from the S-Cl bond points to chlorine. The acid chloride shows R bonded to carbonyl group bonded to a blue chlorine. The carbonyl oxygen atoms are highlighted in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_03_002.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00002">
    <title>Conversion of Carboxylic Acids into Acid Anhydrides</title>
    <para id="para-00004">Acid anhydrides can be derived from two molecules of carboxylic acid by heating to remove 1 equivalent of water. Because of the high temperatures needed, however, only acetic anhydride is commonly prepared this way.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00003">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which 2 moles of acetic acid react at 800 degree C to yield acetic anhydride and water (highlighted in green). Acetic acid shows a methyl group bonded to a carbon single bonded to a green hydroxyl group and double bonded to a pink oxygen. Acetic anhydride shows a methyl group bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a green oxygen that is bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a methyl group. The carbonyl oxygen atoms are highlighted in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_03_003.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00003">
    <title>Conversion of Carboxylic Acids into Esters</title>
    <para id="para-00005">Perhaps the most useful reaction of carboxylic acids is their conversion into esters. There are many methods for accomplishing this, including the S<sub>N</sub>2 reaction of a carboxylate anion with a primary alkyl halide that we saw in <emphasis effect="bold"><link>Section 11.3</link></emphasis>.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00004">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which Sodium butanoate reacts with methyl iodide (SN2 reaction) to yield Methyl butanoate (97%) and sodium iodide. Sodium butanoate shows a propyl group bonded to a carbonyl group that is bonded to an oxygen anion that shows six electrons. Na plus is shown next to oxygen. An arrow from the electrons of oxygen points to the blue methyl group of methyl iodide. An arrow from the CH3-I bond points to I. Methyl butanoate shows a propyl group bonded to a carbonyl group that is bonded to an oxygen bonded to a blue methyl group. The carbonyl oxygen atoms are highlighted in pink. The iodine atoms are highlighted in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_03_004.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00006">Esters can also be synthesized by an acid-catalyzed nucleophilic acyl substitution reaction of a carboxylic acid with an alcohol, a process called the <term id="term-00001">Fischer esterification reaction</term>. Unfortunately, the need for an excess of a liquid alcohol as solvent effectively limits the method to the synthesis of methyl, ethyl, propyl, and butyl esters.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00005">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which benzoic acid reacts with ethanol (highlighted in blue) in the presence of HCl catalyst to yield ethyl benzoate (91%) and water (highlighted in green). Benzoic acid shows benzene bonded to carbonyl group that is bonded to a green hydroxyl group. Ethyl benzoate shows benzene bonded to carbonyl group that is bonded to an ethoxide group (highlighted in blue). The carbonyl oxygens are highlighted in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_03_006.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00007">The mechanism of the Fischer esterification reaction is shown in <link>Figure 21_03_OChem-21-03-005_80485-21-04_M-MechOne</link>. Carboxylic acids are not reactive enough to undergo nucleophilic addition directly, but their reactivity is greatly enhanced in the presence of a strong acid such as HCl or H<sub>2</sub>SO<sub>4</sub>. The mineral acid protonates the carbonyl-group oxygen atom, thereby giving the carboxylic acid a positive charge and rendering it much more reactive toward nucleophiles. Subsequent loss of water from the tetrahedral intermediate yields the ester product.</para>
    <figure class="mechanism-figure scaled-down" id="fig-00006">
    <title>MECHANISM</title>
    <media alt="An illustration shows 4 steps of Fischer esterification in which a carboxylic acid reacts yields an ester. In step 1 the carboxylic acid reacts with pink HA. An arrow from the electrons of carboxyl group points to H of H-A. An arrow from the H-A bond points to A. The product shows R bonded to a carbon that is single bonded to green hydroxyl group and double bonded to a pink oxygen cation bonded to a pink hydrogen. The oxygen shows two electrons. Text reads: Protonation of the carbonyl oxygen activates the carboxylic acid . . .. In step 2 an alcohol (ROH highlighted in blue) reacts with the product of step 1 to yield a tetrahedral intermediate. An arrow from the four electrons of the oxygen in alcohol points to the carbonyl carbon. An arrow from the carbonyl bond points to the carbonyl oxygen. The tetrahedral intermediate shows a carbon dash bonded to R wedge bonded to green hydroxyl group and single bonded to pink hydroxyl group and blue oxygen cation that shows two electrons and is bonded to R’ and hydrogen. In step 3 the tetrahedral intermediate yields another tetrahedral intermediate that shows a carbon dash bonded to R wedge bonded to green oxygen cation that shows two electrons and is bonded to green hydrogen and blue hydrogen. The carbon is bonded to pink hydroxyl group at the top. Text reads: Transfer of a proton from one oxygen atom to another yields a second tetrahedral intermediate and converts the OH group into a good leaving group. In step 4 the second tetrahedral intermediate reacts with water (highlighted in pink) and yields an ester and hydronium ion (highlighted in pink). An arrow from the four electrons of the oxygen in water points to the hydroxyl hydrogen. An arrow from the hydroxyl bond points to the C-OH bond. An arrow from the C-O wedge bond points to oxygen cation. Text reads: Loss of a proton and expulsion of H2O regenerates the acid catalyst and gives the ester product. The ester shows R bonded to a carbonyl compound bonded to blue OR’.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_03_005.jpg"/>
    </media>
    <caption><emphasis effect="bold">Mechanism of Fischer esterification.</emphasis> The reaction is an acid-catalyzed, nucleophilic acyl substitution of a carboxylic acid.</caption>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00008">The net effect of Fischer esterification is substitution of an  – OH group by  – OR′. All steps are reversible, and the reaction typically has an equilibrium constant close to 1. Thus, the reaction can be driven in either direction by the choice of reaction conditions. Ester formation is favored when a large excess of alcohol is used as solvent, but carboxylic acid formation is favored when a large excess of water is present.</para>
    <para id="para-00009">Evidence in support of the mechanism shown in <link>Figure 21_03_OChem-21-03-005_80485-21-04_M-MechOne</link> comes from isotope-labeling experiments. When <sup>18</sup>O-labeled methanol reacts with benzoic acid, the methyl benzoate produced is found to be <sup>18</sup>O-labeled whereas the water produced is unlabeled. Thus, it is the C – OH bond of the carboxylic acid that is broken during the reaction rather than the CO – H bond and the RO – H bond of the alcohol that is broken rather than the R – OH bond.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00007">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which benzoic acid reacts with methanol (highlighted in blue) in the presence of HCl catalyst to yield methyl benzoate and water. In benzoic acid the bond between the carbonyl group and hydroxyl group is green; the hydroxyl group is green. In methanol the oxygen shows an asterisk. Text pointing to the CO-OH bond and CH3O-H bond reads: These bonds are broken. Methyl benzoate shows benzene bonded to carbonyl group bonded to methoxide (highlighted in blue) group (O shows asterisk). In water H is green and OH is blue.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_03_007.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <example id="exam-00001">
    <title>Synthesizing an Ester from an Acid</title>
    <para id="para-00010">How might you prepare the following ester using a Fischer esterification reaction?</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down-30" id="fig-00008">
    <media alt="An illustration shows the structure of an ester. A benzene is bonded to a bromine at C2. C1 is bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to an oxygen bonded to a propyl group.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_03_008.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00011"><title>Strategy</title> Begin by identifying the two parts of the ester. The acyl part comes from the carboxylic acid and the –OR part comes from the alcohol. In this case, the target molecule is propyl <emphasis effect="italics">o</emphasis>-bromobenzoate, so it can be prepared by treating <emphasis effect="italics">o</emphasis>-bromobenzoic acid with 1-propanol.</para>
    <para id="para-00012"><title><span class="cyan-text">Solution</span></title></para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00009">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which o-Bromobenzoic acid reacts with 1-Propanol in the presence of HCl catalyst to yield Propyl o-bromobenzoate and water (highlighted in green). o-Bromobenzoic acid shows benzene with C1 bonded to carbonyl group bonded to green hydroxyl group. C2 is bonded to bromine. Propyl o-bromobenzoate shows benzene with C1 bonded to carbonyl group bonded to propoxide group. C2 is bonded to bromine. The carbonyl oxygens are highlighted in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_03_009.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    </example>
    </section>
